    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
            <ab>
                <lb n="1"/><persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Petronia">Petronia</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Hedone">Hedone</name></persName> fecit sibi
                <lb n="2"/>et <persName><name type="praenomen" key="Lucius"><expan><abbr>L</abbr><ex>ucio</ex></expan></name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Petronius">Petronio</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Philemon">Philemoni</name></persName> filio
                <lb n="3"/>et libertis libertabusquae
                <lb n="4"/>posterisquae eorum.
            </ab>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>Petronia Hedone made (this funerary monument) for herself and for Lucius Petronius
                    Philemon, her son and for her freedmen and freedwomen and for their descendants. </p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>Line 4: There appears to be an interpunct in lībertabusquae between libertis and
                    quae. libertabusquae should be libertabusque.</p> 
                <p>Line 5: posterisquae should be
                    posterisque.</p>
                <p>Triangular shaped interpuncts occur after each word, except at the
                    end of each line.</p>
                <p>The text records an epitaph funded by Petronia Hedone, for
                    herself, her son, Lucius Petronius Philemon, and her freedmen and -women and
                    their descendants. It is noteworthy that there is no mention or depiction of her
                    husband, who would typically be the head of the family. Between both figures
                    there is a deliberate hole meant for libations. The pupils of both figures eye’s
                    have indents. Petronia Hedone’s coiffure resembles the well-known hair style of
                    Vibia Sabina, Hadrian’s wife and Trajan’s niece, who was also a contemporary of
                    Petronia Hedone. The hairstyle involves a center part, then the hair is brushed
                    back over the ears and tied into a bun. It is possible that Petronia Hedone’s
                    hairstyle was deliberately meant to evoke Vibia Sabina, however, the style was
                    also used when depicting many Greek goddesses, so a more general Hellenism
                    influence is also possible. Over her tunic, Petronia Hedone wears a stola, a
                    long outerwear garment, particularly worn by matrons, which is Greek in origin
                    and represents another element of Hellenistic influence. While the inscription
                    is from Rome, it has also been mistakenly attributed to be from Puteoli in the
                    CIL (CIL 10. 2842) and appears twice in EDR as from both Rome and Puteoli.
                    Dating can be assigned to 110-120 CE, based on hairstyle and dress. References D. E.E. Kleiner. 1992.
                    Roman Sculpture. New Haven: Yale University Press. R. Barrow. 2018. Gender,
                    Identity, and the Body in Greek and Roman Sculpture. Cambridge: Cambridge
                    University Press. J. Scheid. 2007. Sacrifices for Gods and Ancestors. In A
                    Companion to Roman Religion, J. Rüpke (Ed.). Oxford: Wiley, pp. 263-272. </p></div>
            

